# JSON Data File Conventions

All tunable gameplay values live in JSON files under `data/`. This is non-negotiable.

## Why
- Balance passes happen without recompiling
- The game is moddable by design
- Agent coding sessions can adjust values without touching code
- Designers can iterate on feel without programmer involvement

## Structure Rules
- One JSON file per system domain (weapons.json, ships.json, damage_types.json)
- Use descriptive string IDs, not numeric IDs (`"laser_mk1"` not `7`)
- Include a `"_comment"` field at the top of each file explaining its purpose
- Nest related properties logically but don't go deeper than 3 levels
- Include units in field names where ambiguous (`damage_per_second`, `range_pixels`, `cooldown_seconds`)

## Validation
- GDScript loading code should validate JSON on load and log clear errors for missing/invalid fields
- Never silently fall back to defaults without logging — failed loads should be noisy
- Use `JSON.parse_string()` in Godot, handle errors explicitly

## Example Pattern
```json
{
  "_comment": "Weapon definitions — see docs/Weapons_Projectiles_Spec.md for field descriptions",
  "laser_mk1": {
    "display_name": "Laser Mk I",
    "archetype": "energy",
    "damage_per_hit": 12,
    "fire_rate_per_second": 4.0,
    "heat_per_shot": 8,
    "power_cost_per_shot": 15,
    "range_pixels": 800,
    "projectile_speed": 1200
  }
}
```
